<TITLE> Justices Rahman, Aziz sworn in </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 8 (bdnews24.com)Two newly appointed judges of the Appellate Division, Shah Abu Nayeem Mominur Rahman and Md Abdul Aziz were sworn in Sunday. Chief Justice MM Ruhul Amin administered the oath at the Judges' Lounge of the Supreme Court. All judges of the Supreme Court were present at the ceremony. Following their swearing in, the Supreme Court Bar Association felicitated the newly appointed judges at the court of the Chief Justice. President Zillur Rahman named the two new judges for the Appellate Division the previous week in line with recommendations of the Supreme Judicial Commission. Justice Shah Abu Nayeem Mominur Rahman was born on November 11, 1944 at Gazipur. He was appointed judge of the High Court Division on June 1, 1996. He will retire on November 24, 2011. Justice Md. Abdul Aziz was born on January 1, 1943 at Jessore. He was appointed High Court Judge on April 27, 1998. Justice Aziz will retire on December 31, this year. Bangabandhu appeal hearing back on track With the new appointments, appeals by those convicted of the murder of independence leader, Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, finally look set to be disposed. "Now the final hearing of the case can resume at the Appellate Division," the chief counsel in the Bangabandhu murder case, Anisul Haq, told bdnews24.com Thursday. "Once the chief justice orders constitution of a bench, there will be no more legal hurdle in resuming hearing of the appeals," additional attorney general M Enanyetur Rahman told bdnews24.com.
